# Testing Rules

## Coverage Expectations

- Every feature must include appropriate automated tests
- Add or update tests when behavior changes
- Prefer targeted tests that validate behavior over low-value tests tied to implementation details
- Do not rely on manual testing alone for important flows

## Test Structure

- Keep tests close to the behavior they verify
- Write tests with clear setup, action, and assertion flow
- Make test names descriptive and behavior-focused
- Use deterministic test data and avoid fragile timing-based assertions

## Naming

- Use consistent naming conventions for test files and test cases
- Name tests to describe the expected behavior
- Prefer names like `shouldCreateUserWhenInputIsValid` over vague names like `worksCorrectly`

## Service Testing

- Each service method must have at least one unit test
- Test both success paths and meaningful failure paths when relevant
- Mock infrastructure boundaries such as databases, APIs, and file systems in unit tests

## Example

```ts
// Avoid
it("works", async () => {
  const result = await pricingService.calculate(input);
  expect(result).toBeDefined();
});
```

```ts
// Prefer
it("shouldApplyDiscountForAnnualPlan", async () => {
  const result = await pricingService.calculate(input);
  expect(result.discountRate).toBe(0.15);
});
```
